<styl>by <m2>By <m0>APRIL WITT<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Religion Writer<ep>
   <m2><ql>
<ql>
<m0>L. <m2><ql>
<m0>Allen Morris, a courtly Miami businessman with a Georgia drawl, isn't in the habit of approaching strangers in hotel lobbies.<ep>
   But Bill Bright and his wife <m1> <m0>Vonette, visiting the Fontainebleau one day in 1960, looked so happy that Morris introduced himself on a whim (--) and met lifelong friends.<ep>
   ``I never did that before or since,'' said Morris, now 82. ``I think the Lord had something to do with it.''<ep>
   Today, Bright, the founder of Campus Crusade for Christ, will receive nearly $1.1 million and the Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion during a private ceremony at Buckingham Palace in London.<ep>
   The honor (--) which carries a purse larger than any other award, including the Nobel Prize (--) is bestowed each year to someone who has shown great originality in advancing humankind's understanding of God or spirituality. Bright's contribution: building Campus Crusade for Christ into the largest evangelical organization in the United States.<ep>
   Morris nominated his old friend for the Templeton, but says, <m1> <m0>``I don't take any credit for this at all.'' <ep>
   Neither does Bright, who makes his world headquarters in Orlando, but travels 300 days a year spreading the Gospel.<ep>
<m1><styl>cxon<m2> <ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   ``I'm just a puny termite somewhere out in space,'' Bright, 74, said last week. ``Forty-five years ago I became a slave of Jesus. Now here I am the recipient of the most-prized award anyone could receive for any pursuit. That's kind of humorous, isn't it? That a slave would be so honored.''<ep>
   <ep>
   Previous recipients of the Templeton, begun by global <m2><ql>
<ql>
PLEASE SEE  CRUSADE,  2D<qr>
<m4>--8.302 inches ( 50p )--from start of measuring to here--<m2><ql>
